# OmniNews: Agentic Intelligence — Video Presentation Script

> **Estimated Duration:** 8–10 minutes  
> **Format:** Screen recording with voiceover narration  
> **Tip:** Show the relevant screen (code, UI, architecture diagram) while reading each section.

---

## SLIDE 1 — Title & Hook
**[Show: OmniNews Dashboard — dark, glowing UI]**

> "What if you could read **every major news source on Earth** — from Reuters to Al Jazeera, from Fox News to the Global Times — and have an AI team of analysts distill it all into a single intelligence briefing, every single day?
>
> That's what **OmniNews: Agentic Insight** does.
>
> This is not a chatbot. This is an autonomous, multi-agent intelligence pipeline — built with Dagster, LangGraph, and Google Gemini — that ingests, clusters, analyzes, and debates global news in real time."

---

## SLIDE 2 — The Problem / Motivation
**[Show: a collage of news websites, or a simple bullet-point slide]**

> "Today's information landscape is broken. There are thousands of news sources, each with their own editorial lens. A story about the same event looks completely different on CNN versus RT versus Al Jazeera.
>
> The average person has **no time** to read across the political spectrum.  
> The average analyst has **no tool** that does it automatically.
>
> We built OmniNews to solve this. Our motivation is threefold:
>
> 1. **Information Overload** — There are too many sources to monitor manually. We needed automation.
> 2. **Media Bias** — No single source tells the whole story. We needed to aggregate across the political spectrum — left, center, right, independent, and even state-backed media.
> 3. **Shallow AI Summaries** — Existing tools just summarize. We wanted AI that **researches**, **critiques its own work**, and **debates itself** from opposing geopolitical perspectives."

---

## SLIDE 3 — System Architecture Overview
**[Show: [docker-compose.yml](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/docker-compose.yml) or a hand-drawn architecture diagram]**

> "OmniNews is a fully containerized, microservices-based system orchestrated by **Dagster**. Here's an overview of the stack:
>
> - **6 Docker containers** running in parallel: Ingestion, Processing, Summarizer, Investigative Agent, Frontend, and the Dagster Webserver.
> - **Supabase PostgreSQL** with pgvector for our database — storing articles, embeddings, clusters, and AI-generated reports.
> - **Dagster** for pipeline orchestration — with sensors that automatically chain jobs together.
> - **LangGraph** for multi-agent workflows — powering the Researcher, Critic, and Reporter agents.
> - **Google Gemini** as the backbone LLM for all analysis.
> - **Tavily** for real-time web search during agent research.
> - **React + Vite** for the frontend intelligence dashboard."

---

## SLIDE 4 — Feature 1: Mass-Scale RSS Ingestion
**[Show: [injest.py](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/ingestion/injest.py), scrolling through the RSS feed list]**

> "The pipeline starts with ingestion. We scrape over **80 RSS feeds** from around the world, carefully categorized by editorial perspective:
>
> - **Global Wire Services**: Reuters, AP, BBC, NPR, CNN, New York Times
> - **Center-Left / International**: Al Jazeera, The Guardian, Deutsche Welle, Financial Times
> - **Left / Progressive**: MSNBC, The Nation, Democracy Now
> - **Center-Right**: Wall Street Journal, The Economist, Politico
> - **Right / Conservative**: Fox News, Washington Times, National Review
> - **Independent / Investigative**: The Intercept, ProPublica, Bellingcat, ICIJ
> - **Economy / Markets**: CNBC, Bloomberg, MarketWatch, OilPrice
> - **Middle East Depth**: Tehran Times, Times of Israel, Haaretz, Daily Sabah
> - **Geopolitics / Think Tanks**: Foreign Affairs, Foreign Policy, Crisis Group, Atlantic Council, Brookings, CFR, CSIS
> - **Pakistan / South Asia**: Dawn, Geo, Express Tribune, The Hindu, Indian Express
> - **Non-Western / State-Backed**: RT, Sputnik, Xinhua, PressTV, Global Times
>
> Each article is filtered by a 7-day window and deduplicated using a `UNIQUE` constraint on the link. This runs on a **bi-daily schedule** — twice a day at 8 AM and 4 PM Pakistan time."

---

## SLIDE 5 — Feature 2: AI-Powered Clustering (NLP)
**[Show: [process.py](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/processing/process.py), specifically the DBSCAN and embedding code]**

> "Once the articles are ingested, the Processing Service kicks in. It does two things:
>
> **Step 1 — Vectorization:** Every article's title and summary are converted into a 384-dimensional vector using `SentenceTransformer` with the `all-MiniLM-L6-v2` model. This captures the **semantic meaning** of each article.
>
> **Step 2 — Clustering:** We run **DBSCAN** — a density-based clustering algorithm — on these vectors using cosine similarity. Articles about the same event are automatically grouped together, even if they use completely different wording.
>
> For example, an article from Reuters saying 'OPEC Cuts Output' and one from Al Jazeera saying 'Oil Alliance Reduces Production' will land in the **same cluster** — because their meaning is the same.
>
> Each cluster gets a unique UUID, creating a single 'story' from multiple sources."

---

## SLIDE 6 — Feature 3: Multi-Agent Summarization (LangGraph)
**[Show: [graph.py](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/agents/graph.py) — the Researcher → Critic → Reporter flow]**

> "This is the heart of OmniNews. For each cluster of articles, we don't just summarize — we run a **full multi-agent intelligence workflow** built with **LangGraph**.
>
> The workflow has three agents:
>
> 1. **The Researcher** — A 'Strategic Intelligence Analyst' that reads all articles in the cluster, then uses **Tavily web search** to gather additional real-time facts. It focuses on conflict zones, economic impact, and filters out sensationalism. It can do multiple research turns for deeper analysis.
>
> 2. **The Critic** — A 'Senior Intelligence Editor' that reviews the Researcher's notes against strict quality criteria: Is it geopolitically relevant? Is it free from sensationalism? Does it have enough depth to assess stability risk? If the notes fail, the Critic sends feedback back to the Researcher for another round.
>
> 3. **The Reporter** — A 'Sovereign Intelligence Analyst' that writes the final briefing. It assigns a **Stability Risk Score** from 1 to 10, analyzes **market impact** on oil, stocks, and currencies, categorizes **source bias** as left/center/right, and extracts **key entities** — people, organizations, and locations.
>
> This system processes up to 15 clusters per run, with 3 running in parallel using a thread pool. Each result is **saved incrementally** — so you see progress in real time, not just at the end."

