## SLIDE 6B — Deep Dive: How the Agents Actually Work
**[Show: [state.py](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/agents/state.py) first, then [graph.py](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/agents/graph.py), highlighting the StateGraph and node functions]**

> "Let me show you how these agents actually work under the hood. This is built on **LangGraph's StateGraph** — a framework for building stateful, multi-step AI workflows.
>
> **The Shared State (The Clipboard):**
> Every agent shares a single state object — think of it as a clipboard passed between them. It contains:
> - The `headline` and `cluster_id` being analyzed
> - A `research_notes` list — this is **append-only**, meaning each Researcher turn *adds* to the notes instead of overwriting them
> - A `critique_feedback` field — where the Critic writes instructions if the research isn't good enough
> - A `turn_count` safety counter — to prevent infinite loops
> - Output fields: `final_report`, `risk_score`, `impact_analysis`, `source_analysis`, and `key_entities`
> - A `status` field that controls routing: `'researching'`, `'critiquing'`, `'reporting'`, or `'done'`
>
> **The Researcher Node — In Detail:**
> When the Researcher runs, it receives the full state. On its first turn, it automatically calls the **Tavily web search tool** with the headline as the query. Tavily returns the top 3 real-time search results, which get appended to `research_notes`. On subsequent turns — if the Critic sent feedback — the Researcher reads the feedback, generates a follow-up search query using Gemini, then searches again.
>
> The Researcher also has **strategic priorities** baked into its system prompt:
> - Prioritize conflict zones: Iran, Middle East, Russia/Ukraine, China/Taiwan
> - Focus on economic impact: Oil, Stocks, Employment, Inflation
> - Apply a **sensationalism filter**: Ignore celebrity gossip unless it's tied to political corruption
>
> **The Critic Node — The Quality Gate:**
> The Critic receives the accumulated research notes and runs them through a strict compliance check:
> 1. Is it geopolitical or economic in focus?
> 2. Is it free from sensationalism?
> 3. Does it have enough depth for a stability risk assessment?
>
> If the notes pass, it sets `status` to `'reporting'` and the graph moves to the Reporter. If they fail, it writes detailed feedback like *'FAIL: Too focused on domestic politics — pivot to the regional escalation implications'* and sets `status` back to `'researching'`, sending it back to the Researcher for another round.
>
> **The Reporter Node — Structured Output:**
> The Reporter takes all of the accumulated research and writes the final intelligence briefing. But it doesn't just write free-form text — it produces **structured output** with specific tags that the system parses:
> - `[RISK_SCORE: 7]` — parsed into an integer for the dashboard's color-coded risk index
> - `[IMPACT: ...]` — parsed into the impact analysis field
> - `[SOURCES_JSON]...[/SOURCES_JSON]` — a JSON block of sources with bias classification
> - `[ENTITIES_JSON]...[/ENTITIES_JSON]` — a JSON block of people, organizations, and locations
>
> The code then strips these tags and presents the clean Markdown report on the dashboard.
>
> **The Router — Conditional Edges:**
> The graph uses a [router](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/agents/graph.py#298-309) function to decide where to go next after each node. It checks the `turn_count` against a limit — 1 turn for standard briefings, 5 turns for deep-dives — and the `status` field. This is how the Researcher-Critic loop works: the Critic can send the state back to the Researcher up to the turn limit.
>
> **Rate Limit Handling:**
> All LLM calls go through a [safe_llm_invoke](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/agents/graph.py#46-74) wrapper that implements **exponential backoff**. If Gemini returns a 429 (rate limit), 503, or 502 error, the system waits and retries up to 5 times with increasing delays. This is critical because we're making dozens of LLM calls per run across parallel threads.
>
> **The Editorial Filter:**
> Before any agent even runs, each cluster goes through an [is_editorial_fit](file:///c:/Users/musta/OneDrive/Desktop/new_etl/summarizer/summarize.py#23-68) function that checks if the headline is worth analyzing. This filters out lifestyle, entertainment, and low-impact stories so the agents only spend time on strategically relevant news."

